1. What is HTML?
  1. HTML is a markup language for creating web documents and pages
  2. Hyper Text Markup Language
  3. NOT a programming language ( uses a set of markup tags)
2. HTML Tags
  1. HTML tags define HTML element which is an individual component of an HTML document or web page
  2. Keywords surrounded by angle brackets
3. Page Structure

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
    <head>
        <title>My Webpage</title>
    </head>
    <body>
        <p>This is my first web page</p>
    </body>
</html>

4. Common Doctype declarations

HTML5
<!DOCTYPE html>

HTML4.01 (DTD = document type definition)
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.01 Transitional//EN"
"http://www.w3.org/TR/html4/loose.dtd">

XHTML 1.0 (extensive hyper text markup language)
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD XHTML 1.0 Transitional//EN"
"http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml1/DTD/xhtml1-transitional.dtd">

5. Closing Tags

Not all tags have closing tags like <p></p>

Some tags can close themselves like line-break tag - <br>
Self closing line-break tag - <br />

6. Common Tags

Paragraph<p>
Headings <h1> - <h6>
Link <a>
Image <img>
Unordered List <ul>
Ordered List <ol>
List Item <li>
Table <table>
Form <form>
Input <input>
Button <button>
Line Break <br>
Horizontal Rule <hr>
Division <div>
HTML <html>
Head <head>
Body <body>
Strong <strong> - increase font weight

7. Attributes

Tags can also have "attributes" which include extra bits of information about that tag/element.
Attributes appear in the tag inside of quotation marks.

<tag attribute="value"></tag>
<a href="http://google.com">Click</a>
<h1 id="myHeading"></h1>

Could be both sigle/double quotes - usually double quotes.

8. Block Level Elements

Always starts on a new line
Takes up full available width

<div>
<h1> - <h6>
<p>
<form>

9. Inline level Elements
  - Does not start on a new line
  - Takes only width necessary

<span>
<a>
<img>


10. Creating a Web Page
  - Use a text editor or IDE to create your HTML document
  - Add elements, tags, attributes, etc
  - Save file with a .html extension
  - Open it up in a brower - no server needed




11. Create your first webpage using HTML

<h1>Links</h1>
<a href="http://google.com" target="_blank">>Link to Google</a>


taget="_blank": link click opens up a new tab


12. Lists and tables

13. Basic Styling - Project on Basic CSS

<div id="container">
</div>

id vs class: id is usually used once whereas class is used multiple times (also in .css)






------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


HTML 5


- New Tags & Elements (<div>, <span>)
- Syntax is no longer based on SGML, but is backward compatible with earlier versions of HTML

New APIs
HTML5 specifies scripting application programming interfaces that can be used with JavaScript
  - Canvas & SVG
  - Drag and Drop
  - Web Storage
  - Geolocation (good for cross-platform app)
  - IndexedDB (low-level API for client side storage of structured data)
  - Web Audio
  - Editable Content (take virtually any content and make it editable.)
  - App Cache



1. Web Storage
  - Local Storage
    - items stored until deleted
    - setItem: has to be string
  - Session Storage
    - items stored only during the session
  1.1. Console Log
    - you can check it with F12 in Chrome (fn + f12 key)
    - document.getElementById('name').innerHTML=localStorage.name
    - document.getElementById.name.innerHTML=sessionStorage.name
  1.2. to check the session/local storage, check application tab in (fn + f12 key)



